{"title_page": "Cabin (ship)", "text_new": "{{short description|Enclosed space generally on a ship}}\n{{Other uses|Cabin (disambiguation)}}\n{{Redirect|Berthing||Berth (disambiguation)}}\n{{Refimprove|article|date=December 2008}}\nA '''cabin''' or '''berthing''' is an enclosed space generally on a [[ship]] or an [[aircraft]]. A cabin which protrudes above the level of a ship's [[deck (ship)|deck]] may be referred to as a '''deckhouse'''.\n[[File:Vasa-great cabin-2.jpg|right|thumb|Interior of the great cabin of the 17th century Swedish warship ''[[Vasa (ship)|Vasa]]''.]]\n\n==Sailing ships==\n[[File:Grand Turk(33).jpg|thumb|Great cabin on the ''[[Grand Turk (frigate)|Grand Turk]]'', a replica of a three-masted English 18th century-frigate.]]\n[[File:Flickr - Official U.S. Navy Imagery - The CNO reviews his speech..jpg|right|thumb|Commanding officer\u2019s in-port cabin aboard the American aircraft carrier [[USS Nimitz (CVN 68)|USS ''Nimitz'' (CVN-68)]].]]\n\nIn [[sailing ships]], the officers and paying passengers would have an individual or shared cabin.  The [[Captain (nautical)|captain]] or [[commanding officer]]  would occupy the \"great cabin\" that normally spanned the width of the [[stern]] and had large windows. \n\nOn a warship, it was a privileged area, separate from the rest of the ship, for the exclusive use of the captain. In large warships, the cabin was subdivided into day and night cabins (bedrooms) by movable panels, called ''[[Bulkhead (partition)|bulk-heads]]'', that could be removed in time of battle to leave the cabin clear for the gunners to use the [[chase gun|stern chasers]] several of which were usually stationed in the cabin.\n\nOn large [[Three-decker|three decker]] warships in the [[age of sail]] the captain's cabin was sometimes appropriated by the [[Admiral]]. The captain would be consigned to the cabin below on the middle [[gun deck|gun-deck]].\n\n==Modern warships==\n[[File:Banettes mg 5182.jpg|thumb|Bunks on the French aircraft carrier [[French aircraft carrier Clemenceau (R98)|''Clemenceau'']].]]\nIn most modern [[warship]]s, the commanding officer has a main cabin\u2014the '''in-port cabin''', often adjacent to the ship's central control room ([[operations room]])\u2014and a '''sea cabin''' adjacent to the [[Bridge (ship)|bridge]]. Thus, when likely to be called from sleep or attending to administration, the commanding officer can go to the sea cabin and thereby be able to appear at the bridge or operations room immediately. The sea cabin is sparsely equipped, containing just a bunk, a desk, and basic toilet facilities. The in-port cabin is more lavishly furnished, with separate bedroom and combination [[sitting room]]/office, and more elaborate toiletry facilities.<ref>{{cite book|title=Aircraft Carriers at War|page=201|author=James L. Holloway III|publisher=Naval Institute Press|date=2007|isbn=978-1-59114-391-8}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=200,000&nbsp;Miles Aboard the Destroyer Cotten|author=C. Snelling Robinson|page=11|publisher=The Kent State University Press|date=2000|isbn=978-0-87338-698-2}}</ref>\n\nFor ships intended to act as [[flagship]]s, like the former [[United States Navy]] [[aircraft carrier]] {{USS|Lexington|CV-16|6}}\u2014now a [[museum ship]]\u2014the admiral also has a sea cabin (adjacent to the captain's sea cabin) and an in-port cabin, in addition to the captain's cabins. [[Frank Jack Fletcher|Admiral Fletcher]]'s sea cabin in the aircraft carrier {{USS|Yorktown|CV-5|6}} during [[World War II]] had a bed, an easy chair, a table, and a shower.<ref>{{cite book|title=Carrier Lexington|author=Hugh Irvin Power|page=100|publisher=Texas A&M University Press|date=1996|isbn=978-0-89096-681-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|page=83|title=Black Shoe Carrier Admiral: Frank Jack Fletcher at Coral Sea, Midway, and Guadalcanal|author=John B. Lundstrom|publisher=Naval Institute Press|date=2006|isbn=978-1-59114-475-5}}</ref>\n\nThe captain's in-port cabin of the [[USS Iowa (BB-61)]] is unique for a modern warship in having been outfitted with a bathtub, as she was used to take President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Roosevelt]] to the [[Cairo Conference]]. Roosevelt, who had been crippled in 1921, was unable to make effective use of a shower facility. An elevator was was also temporarily added to Iowa for the voyage, but was removed shortly after the trip.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kaplan |first1=Philip |title=Battleships: WWII Evolution of the Big Guns |date=2015 |publisher=Pen and Sword |isbn=9781783463077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mather |first1=Kate |title=Rare photo found of elevator added to battleship Iowa for FDR |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-photo-elevator-battleship-roosevelt-20130903-story.html |website=latimes.com |publisher=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=6 April 2020 |date=3 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nOfficers normally have their own cabins\u2014sometimes referred to as '''staterooms'''\u2014which double as their offices. Some senior [[petty officer]]s may have cabins for similar reasons.\n\nSailors sleep in [[Berth (sleeping)|berthing areas]].\n\n==Passenger ships==\nIn ships carrying [[passenger]]s, they are normally accommodated in cabins, taking the terminology familiar to seafarers. First-class cabins were traditionally referred to as '''staterooms''', and today many cruise lines now prefer to refer to passenger cabins as staterooms or suites.\n\n==Cabin crawl==\nIn [[cruise ship]] terms, a cabin crawl is an event where [[passenger]]s tour the cabins of fellow passengers. A cruise ship may also offer a cabin crawl of cabins or suites which did not sell for a particular sailing. The purpose of a cabin crawl is to give passengers an idea of the space and layout of various cabin options for their next cruise. Cabin crawls are normally organized prior to a cruise, through cruise-fan websites.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cruise Critic Board|url=http://www.cruisecritic.com|website=Cruise Critic|accessdate=7 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cabin Crawl|url=http://www.cabincrawl.com|website=Cabin Crawl|accessdate=7 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Spacecraft==\nIn [[spacecraft]], cabins are required to fully supply food and [[oxygen]] for their crew. On missions lasting a year or longer, the cabins have to be self-sustaining, i.e. replenish their own water and oxygen. The space cabin for any long-range manned mission is expected to be reasonably spacious, with approximately 28 cubic metres allotted to each occupant. In addition, cabins have life support systems that should have the capability to meet a variety of off-nominal conditions, including cabin fires, depressurization, and component shutdown or failure. Frequently, these conditions occur so quickly that recovery can be provided only by automatic control systems. In the late 1960s, several experimental ground facilities were developed to evaluate regenerative life support systems for crewed space flight.<ref>{{cite web|last=Averill|first=R.D.|title=A systems analysis of a regenerative cabin atmosphere control system|url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/search.jsp?R=19690010288|work=Langley Research Center|publisher=NASA|publicationdate=1968|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Berth (sleeping)]]\n*[[Compartment (ship)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Rooms]]\n[[Category:Ship compartments]]\n[[Category:Nautical terminology]]\n\n[[de:Kabine]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Enclosed space generally on a ship}}\n{{Other uses|Cabin (disambiguation)}}\n{{Redirect|Berthing||Berth (disambiguation)}}\n{{Refimprove|article|date=December 2008}}\nA '''cabin''' or '''berthing''' is an enclosed space generally on a [[ship]] or an [[aircraft]]. A cabin which protrudes above the level of a ship's [[deck (ship)|deck]] may be referred to as a '''deckhouse'''.\n[[File:Vasa-great cabin-2.jpg|right|thumb|Interior of the great cabin of the 17th century Swedish warship ''[[Vasa (ship)|Vasa]]''.]]\n\n==Sailing ships==\n[[File:Grand Turk(